<dl id="n12113j"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12113j">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12113j"> 113(j)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> <font face="wake">X</font> J. adds absurd detail</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> la pluie persistante emp&ecirc;chait la moisson et la r&eacute;colte mena&ccedil;ait de se g&acirc;ter sur pied. L&apos;abb&eacute; prend sa faucille, conduit tout son monde &agrave; l&apos;ouvrage et, tandis que les moines commencent &agrave; couper sous l&apos;ond&eacute;e, il dispose quatre bretons &ldquo; pleins de religion&rdquo; aux quatre extr&eacute;mit&eacute;s du champ et lui-m&ecirc;me se place au milieu. Tous travaillaient ainsi pleins d&apos;ardeur et le soleil se mit &agrave; luire qui s&eacute;cha la terre et les javelles. Et Jonas ajoute m&ecirc;me, entra&icirc;n&eacute; peut-&ecirc;tre par son admiration, que dans les environs la pluie continuait &agrave; tomber. <br><font color="green">[&hellip; the persistent rain hindered the harvest and the crops risked being ruined as they grew. The abbot took his sickle and led everyone to work and, while the monks started to reap beneath the downpour, he placed four Bretons &lsquo;full of religion&rsquo; at the four corners of the field and he put himself in the middle. Everyone worked assiduously and the sun began to shine and it dried the earth and the sheaves. And Jonas, perhaps carried away by his admiration, added that in the surrounding area the rain continued to fall.]</font> <small> <a name="STCM" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#STCM"><cite title="source">Saint Colomban</cite></a> (1905) 46</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
